# Credit Risk Machine Learning Pipeline

## Overview

This project implements an end-to-end credit risk prediction system designed using industry-style data engineering and machine learning practices. The objective is to estimate the probability that a loan applicant will default using structured financial history data from multiple relational sources.

The system emphasizes reproducibility, modular architecture, SQL-first feature engineering, and interpretable modeling suitable for regulated financial environments.

---

## Project Objectives

The pipeline is designed to demonstrate production-oriented skills across:

* relational data ingestion
* schema-layered warehouse design
* SQL-based data profiling and feature engineering
* predictive modeling for default risk
* model interpretability using SHAP
* deployment through an interactive prediction interface

This repository reflects workflows commonly used in credit risk analytics teams.

---

## Architecture

```mermaid
graph TD;
    RawData(.csv files in Data/Raw/) -->|Ingestion Python Script| PostgreSql[(PostgreSQL Staging DB)];
    PostgreSql -->|Feature Engineering SQL| FeaturesDB[(Features Database)];
    FeaturesDB -->|Scikit-Learn/XGBoost| ModelTraining(Model Training & Tuning);
    ModelTraining -->|Generate Artifacts| Artifacts(Save Code/Parameters);
    
    Users((User)) -->|Input Data| Streamlit[Streamlit Web App];
    Artifacts -->|Load Model| Streamlit;
    Streamlit -->|Output Prediction| Users;

    subgraph Data Engineering (Current Focus)
    RawData
    PostgreSql
    end

    subgraph MLOps & Frontend (Planned)
    FeaturesDB
    ModelTraining
    Streamlit
    end

    style RawData fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px;
    style Streamlit fill:#ccf,stroke:#f66,stroke-width:2px,color:#fff;

The project follows a layered data pipeline structure:

Raw CSV Files
→ PostgreSQL Staging Layer (TEXT ingestion)
→ Clean Typed Layer
→ Feature Engineering Layer
→ Modeling Layer
→ Streamlit Prediction Interface

### Staging Layer

All datasets are ingested as TEXT to ensure ingestion reliability despite inconsistent source schemas. This mirrors industry ingestion strategies used when handling heterogeneous external datasets.

Tables ingested:

* application_train
* application_test
* bureau
* bureau_balance
* credit_card_balance
* installments_payments
* pos_cash_balance
* previous_application

---

## Data Engineering Workflow

Key engineering components implemented:

* automated ingestion from CSV to PostgreSQL
* schema-isolated staging environment
* reproducible loading pipeline
* SQL-first profiling strategy
* layered transformation pipeline design

Future layers convert raw staging tables into typed analytical feature tables.

---

## Feature Engineering Strategy

Feature construction will combine:

* application-level attributes
* bureau credit history aggregates
* previous loan behavior
* installment payment patterns
* credit utilization indicators

The modeling dataset will be constructed as a single observation per applicant (SK_ID_CURR).

---

## Modeling Approach

Models implemented:

* Logistic Regression (baseline probability model)
* Random Forest (nonlinear ensemble benchmark)
* XGBoost (gradient boosting production candidate)

Evaluation metrics:

* ROC-AUC
* Precision-Recall
* Feature importance stability
* Business interpretation of false positives vs false negatives

Explainability:

* SHAP value attribution for individual predictions
* global feature influence analysis

---

## Deployment

A Streamlit application will allow:

* manual applicant input
* default probability prediction
* feature contribution interpretation
* model transparency for decision support

